Condition: This question will only be considered if both of the following occur: (a) By December 31, 2025, any member country of the United Nations has officially introduced a resolution aimed at regulating artificial intelligence (AI) on a global scale. The resolution must seek to establish guidelines, standards, or laws applicable to the development, deployment, or use of AI technologies across multiple countries. The introduction of such a resolution must be confirmed by an official UN document or announcement. In the absence of direct UN confirmation, credible reports from at least three major news organizations (BBC, The Guardian, Reuters, Bloomberg, New York Times, Washington Post) will be considered sufficient evidence. The resolution must be formally presented in a UN session or committee for discussion or voting. Preliminary discussions, proposals, or mentions that do not lead to a formal introduction do not count towards this question's resolution. (b) Before January 1, 2030, a machine learning model is used to predict the outcome of a national election in any country with a population exceeding 1 million people, and achieves an accuracy rate of over 90% compared to the official election results. The prediction must be made public before the election occurs and must cover the majority of elected positions or the overall election result. The accuracy of the prediction must be verified by a reputable source, such as a major news organization (BBC, The Guardian, New York Times, Washington Post) or an academic publication. In the event that multiple machine learning models meet these criteria, the question will resolve as Yes if at least one model achieves the specified accuracy. Machine learning models used for internal purposes by political parties or governments without public disclosure do not count towards this question's resolution.
